{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524908"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:09:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:09:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14035"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14035"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.08,0.19,0.63,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105989"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6684"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88464"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2934"},{"type":"tags","id":"2961"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"},{"type":"tags","id":"6361"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13795"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38849"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105989"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of generalised muscle pain and weakness. She also reports dark-coloured urine. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and hypercholesterolaemia. Her medications include metformin, lisinopril, and atorvastatin 80 mg daily, which was started two weeks ago. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. She has diffuse muscle tenderness on palpation. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 260 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatine kinase: 15,000 U/L (26-192)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 250 U/L (0-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 300 U/L (0-35).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Along with intravenous fluids, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dose-reduce atorvastatin given high cardiovascular risk","Switch high-intensity statin (atorvastatin) to pravastatin","Urgent haemodialysis as Cr \u003E250\u03bcmol/L","Discontinue atorvastatin","Commence short-course oral prednisone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and biochemical features suggestive of rhabdomyolysis and acute kidney injury (AKI), likely secondary to high-dose atorvastatin therapy. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ediscontinue atorvastatin and start intravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E. Statins, particularly at high doses, can rarely cause rhabdomyolysis, which can lead to AKI. The elevated creatine kinase, liver enzymes, and creatinine, along with the clinical symptoms of muscle pain and dark urine, are consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDose-reducing atorvastatin \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be insufficient given the patient has rhabdomyolysis secondary to statin medication, the safest practice is to discontinue the medication whilst the patient is unwell. There is no suggestion in the stem that the patient has a high cardiovascular risk, and even if so, addressing the current episode of rhabdomyolysis is the management priority. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Eswitching high-intensity statin (atorvastatin) to pravastatin\u003C/strong\u003E in the acute setting is also incorrect. Both options could lead to further muscle damage and worsening of kidney function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing short-course oral prednisone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in the management of statin-induced rhabdomyolysis. Corticosteroids are not a standard treatment for this condition and could potentially worsen the patient\u0027s diabetes control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent haemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary in severe cases of rhabdomyolysis with life-threatening hyperkalaemia or severe AKI unresponsive to fluid therapy. However, it is not the first-line management and should be considered only if the patient does not respond to conservative measures or develops severe complications. Cr \u0026gt;250\u03bcmol/L is an arbitrary criterion and not an emergency indication for dialysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key management steps for statin-induced rhabdomyolysis include discontinuation of the offending statin, aggressive intravenous fluid administration to maintain good urine output and prevent further kidney injury, monitoring of electrolytes (particularly potassium), and supportive care. Close monitoring of renal function and creatine kinase levels is essential. In most cases, the condition improves with these measures, although recovery may take several weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Statins can cause rhabdomyolysis, leading to acute kidney injury.","Risk factors for statin-induced rhabdomyolysis include high-dose therapy, advanced age, and concomitant use of certain medications.","Discontinuation of the statin and aggressive intravenous fluid resuscitation are key management steps in statin-induced rhabdomyolysis."],"references":["Bosch X, Poch E, Grau JM. Rhabdomyolysis and acute kidney injury [published correction appears in N Engl J Med. 2011 May 19;364(20):1982]. N Engl J Med. 2009;361(1):62-72. Available from: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra0801327"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88464"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14035"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88464"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-15T18:19:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T18:20:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6684"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105989"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms